**Steps to Reproduce**:

In the following example, the compiler doesn't emit any visible sequence points corresponding to the closing braces 1 and 2:
```csharp
object SyncFoo() 
{
    using (var d = new Disposable())
    {
        using (var d1 = new Disposable())
        {
            return null;
        } <-- closing brace 1
    } <-- closing brace 2
}
```
But if we use `await using` statement instead of the second `using` the compiler emits a not-hidden sequence point corresponding to the closing brace 2, which seems to be unreachable:
```csharp
async Task<object> AsyncFoo() 
{
    using (var d = new Disposable())
    {
        await using (var d1 = new AsyncDisposable())
        {
            return null;
        } <-- closing brace 1
    } <-- closing brace 2. Sequence point is here
}
```

This breaks sequence points-based coverage tools (like Visual Studio's one) because the coverage metric for `AsyncFoo` method will never be 100%:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/17826751/114719318-9ef09700-9d3f-11eb-9c25-0d29c087cd5a.png)

Instead of `using` parent block, there may be any other option: try-catch, try-finally, just { }. In all cases, there will be an uncovered sequence point on the parent block's closing brace.

Shouldn't the sequence point be hidden in this case?

